[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:
-----------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 63.7% of the global newly reported cases and 65.5% of newly reported fatalities for this 24-hour period. If one corrects for this within the region, note that there is a backlog of 31 422 cases reported today by Chile, thereby artificially increasing the proportion of new cases reported to WHO in the region, and proportion of newly confirmed cases reported by Chile relative to the other countries in the region. Adjusting the numerator and denominator within the region to account for the 4757 newly confirmed cases in the region reported by Chile, Brazil reported 41.5% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, USA reported 33.2%, Chile 5.7%, Mexico 5.5%, and Peru 5.0%. The same 5 countries at the top.

The European region reported 10.7% of the global newly reported cases and 13.8% of the newly confirmed deaths in the region, Russia reported 40.3% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Turkey 7.4%, Sweden 6.4%, the UK 5.8%, Ukraine 4.3%, and Belarus and Armenia at 3.4% each. Again, same countries, minor juggling of orders and percentages on a daily basis.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 11.1% of the global newly reported cases and 9.9% of global newly reported fatalities. Pakistan reported 26.7% of the regional newly reported cases followed by Saudi Arabia 24.5%, Iran 13.0%, Iraq 7.8%, Egypt 6.8%, Qatar 5.5%, and Oman 4.0%.

The African region reported 3.8% of the global newly reported cases and 2.6% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 59.0% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria 8.5%, Ghana 5.7%, Cote d'Ivoire 5.6%, Kenya 2.7%, Mauritania 2.5%, and Central African Republic 2.2%. While South Africa and Nigeria are consistently number 1 and number 2 in terms of 24 hour increase in cases, in the last 24 hours, other countries have less consistent reporting patterns and vary considerably from day to day.

The Western Pacific region reported 0.48% of the global newly reported cases and 0.19% of global fatalities. The Philippines reported 52.2% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Singapore 28.2%, South Korea 6.7%, Japan 4.6%, and China 4.1%. The outbreak associated with the Beijing Seafood markets continues to bring China to prominence in terms of daily newly confirmed cases.

The South East Asia region reported 10.2% of the global newly reported cases and 8.1% of global fatalities. India reported 69.4% of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 21.6%, Indonesia 5.6%, and Nepal 3.2%. Same countries, same order as in previous days.

Impression: Europe seems to be stabilizing at a significantly lower rate, although Russia is still reporting 7000+ new cases a day (down from 8000+ per day). The Eastern Mediterranean has surpassed the European region with Pakistan reporting 5-6000+ cases a day and Saudi Arabia reporting 4000+ cases a day. South East Asia is approaching parity with the European and Eastern Mediterranean regions with India reporting 8000-10 000+ cases a day. The Eastern Mediterranean region has surpassed the European region for the past 3 days in terms of newly confirmed cases. The Americas region is reporting around 70 000 cases a day with Brazil usually reporting 25 000-30 000+ cases a day, and the USA at 20 000-25 000+ a day. In the Africa region, the regional proportion is slowly climbing, with South Africa reporting in the 3000-4000+ range daily, and in the Western Pacific region, they are maintaining a very low rate compared with the other regions, with the Philippines averaging 400+ cases per day (Singapore had been reporting twice as many cases per day for a period of time but has dropped back over the past couple of weeks).

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 18 Jun 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. Europe has significantly decreased. The Americas region continues to increase, as does South East Asia, which is approaching parity with the European region in terms of daily newly confirmed cases and the Eastern Mediterranean, which has overtaken the European region; the African region is noticeably increasing as well. The Americas region continues to greatly outnumber all other regions for daily reporting, with an artificial major spike today related to the report from Chile including previously confirmed cases that had not been reported.. - Mod.MPP]

